PART II: THE PHYSICS
═══════════════════════════════════════════


EXECUTION
=========

There is no execution model.

In traditional computing:
    1. Fetch instruction
    2. Decode instruction
    3. Execute instruction
    4. Write result
    5. GOTO 1

In XYZT:
    Topology exists.
    Signals propagate.
    Collisions happen.

That's not a simplification of execution.
That IS execution.

The question "when does the program run?" has no meaning.
The program runs by existing.
The only time it doesn't run is when nothing changes.
That's T-break: no distinction event, no computation.
T still flows. The substrate doesn't stop because the marks
stop changing. But nothing new is written on the canvas.


NOISE FLOOR
===========

When is a distinction still a distinction?

Signals decay. Energy attenuates. At some point a "1" has so
little energy it's indistinguishable from "0". That boundary
is the noise floor.

    E_noise — minimum energy for a valid distinction

    E(p) > E_noise:  position p holds a distinction. It's alive.
    E(p) ≤ E_noise:  position p holds nothing. It's dead.

The noise floor is not a design choice. It's a property of the
substrate — thermal noise in copper, shot noise in photons,
quantization error in FPGA fixed-point.

    On FPGA (Q8.8 fixed-point): E_noise = 1 LSB = 0.00390625
    On PCB (50Ω trace): E_noise = kT*B (thermal noise floor)

A lattice position that decays below E_noise has no distinction.
It's not zero. It's NOTHING. The distinction ceased to exist.
This is not failure. This is the lattice's garbage collector.
Dead positions free themselves. No explicit deallocation.


TIMING
======

(A+B)² only works if A and B arrive at the junction together.

If A propagates through 50 cells and B through 3, A arrives
late. The collision is wrong. This is not a bug to work around.
This is a design parameter to use.

Impedance controls propagation velocity:

    v(Z) = 1 / √(L * C)

    Higher Z = higher L = slower propagation
    Lower Z = lower L = faster propagation

Path delay from position A to junction J:

    delay(A→J) = Σ (dx / v(Z_i)) for each cell i on the path

To synchronize two inputs at a junction:

    delay(A→J) must equal delay(B→J)

This is achieved by adjusting impedance along each path.
High-Z segments slow the fast path. Low-Z segments speed
the slow path. The impedance profile IS the timing diagram.

No clock. No setup/hold constraints.
Impedance-matched path lengths = synchronized collision.

In the 2-bit adder: carry from bit 0 must arrive at the
bit 1 junction before the XOR completes. The carry path's
impedance profile determines whether this works.
Z-depth handles this naturally: Z=1 computes before Z=2 reads.


OBSERVATION
===========

Reading IS a collision.

To observe position P, you couple a probe at P.
The probe has impedance Z_probe.

    Z_probe = high → sees everything, disturbs nothing
    Z_probe = low  → drains the state, destroys what it reads

There is no free read. Observation costs energy.
The cost is determined by the impedance ratio between
probe and cavity. This is not a design choice.
This is physics asserting itself.

    Observation tax: signal_remaining = signal * Z_probe / (Z_probe + Z_cavity)

Non-destructive read: Z_probe >> Z_cavity.
Full extraction: Z_probe = Z_cavity (impedance matched).

The model reads the lattice through high-Z probes.
It sees the state. The state barely notices.

Self-observation: a region probing itself creates a feedback
loop. The observation output feeds back as input. This is not
a pathology — it's the mechanism behind self-referential
computation. But uncontrolled feedback oscillates. Controlled
feedback (impedance-damped) is how the lattice reflects on
its own state. This is where the phi experiments live.


ENERGY
======

Signals decay. Cavities leak. Q is finite.

    Energy at position P after time T:
        E(t) = E(0) * exp(-t / (Q * period))

Computation is transient unless energy is replenished.
This is not a bug. This is the natural clock.

    Active lattice:  periodic injection sustains signal.
    Passive lattice: single injection, computation decays.
    Dead lattice:    no energy, no distinction, no computation.

Energy determines what's alive. Impedance determines what computes.

The lattice does not need to be synchronous.
Each cavity has its own resonant frequency.
Each region can run at its own rate.
Physics IS the scheduler. What has energy, computes.
What doesn't, sleeps. No priority queue.


SIGNAL RESTORATION
==================

Long computations die before they complete. Q=188 means
188 round-trips, not infinite. A 50-stage pipeline loses
signal before the end.

Restoration = re-injection at resonant frequency.

    Gain region: a cavity whose impedance structure
    amplifies signals that match its resonance.
    Signals at the right frequency grow.
    Signals at the wrong frequency decay.
    That's frequency-selective amplification from geometry.

This is the XYZT transistor. Not a switch. An amplifier.
A region of the lattice where energy flows IN (from a supply)
and coherent signal flows OUT (to the next stage).

The supply is a steady injection at the cavity's frequency.
The signal modulates when the injection couples to the cavity.
Presence of signal = amplification. Absence = no coupling.

    Supply + signal → amplified signal (gain > 1)
    Supply + no signal → supply absorbed by boundary (gain = 0)

Gain regions placed between pipeline stages restore signal.
The computation can propagate indefinitely.
The cost: energy input at each gain region.

Formally proven: if supply covers decay loss, pipeline
holds target signal level forever. Not 188 ticks.
Not 10,000 ticks. All ticks. By induction.
(Lean 4: sustained_steady_state.)


BOUNDARIES
==========

What separates one computation from another?
Impedance walls.

A region surrounded by max-Z positions is isolated.
Signals cannot cross. Energy cannot leak.
That's process isolation. No privilege rings.
No kernel mode. Just: physics can't get through.

To open a boundary: lower the impedance.
To close it: raise it back.

    Region A: positions (0-15, 0-15, *, *)  Z_boundary = max
    Region B: positions (16-31, 0-15, *, *)  Z_boundary = max

A and B cannot interfere. Not by policy. By physics.

To communicate: create a controlled opening.
A thin low-Z channel between regions.
That's a port. Impedance-matched for signal integrity.
Mismatched for isolation when closed.

This IS the kernel. Not code. Impedance topology.


RECONFIGURATION
===============

Can you change the topology while signals propagate?
Yes. That's called learning.

    To rewire:
        1. Raise Z at the old connection (disconnect).
        2. Lower Z at the new connection (connect).

Signals in flight see the impedance change.
If the change is slow (adiabatic), signals adapt smoothly.
If the change is fast, signals reflect and scatter.

The model reconfigures by writing impedance values.
Not instructions. Not code. Just: change Z at position P.

    Hebbian learning = strengthen connections that correlate.
        Correlated edges: lower Z (more conductive).
        Uncorrelated edges: raise Z (more resistive).
        Anti-correlated edges: lower Z (structure detected).
        Noise (50%): raise Z (no signal, atrophy).

The lattice learns by adjusting its own impedance.
The program rewrites itself by changing its own physics.


CROSSING
========

Two signals on perpendicular channels cross in the lattice.

The channels are open paths (full conductance) surrounded by
impedance walls (zero conductance). Each signal is confined
to its own channel. At the crossing point, both channels are
open, but each signal propagates along its own axis.

    Horizontal signal → crosses vertical channel → continues horizontal.
    Vertical signal → crosses horizontal channel → continues vertical.

Crosstalk = 0. Not "low." Zero.
Any escape path from one channel to the other goes through
an impedance wall. The wall kills it. Proven.

This extends to 3D: three orthogonal channels at one crossing.
Three signals delivered. Six crosstalk directions blocked.

This removes the planar graph limitation.
Arbitrary circuit topologies can be routed in 2D or 3D.
(Lean 4: crossing_with_confinement, crossing3d_with_confinement.)



