PART III: THE ARCHITECTURE
═══════════════════════════════════════════


COMPOSITION
===========

Z-depth is the pipeline.

    Z = 0: input layer (raw signals)
    Z = 1: first collision layer (first computation)
    Z = 2: second collision layer (computation on computations)
    Z = n: depth n

Coupling between layers is controlled by inter-layer impedance:

    Strong coupling (low Z between layers):
        Output at Z=1 immediately drives Z=2.
        Fast pipeline. Tight feedback.

    Weak coupling (high Z between layers):
        Output at Z=1 barely reaches Z=2.
        Isolation. Independent computation.

    No coupling (max Z between layers):
        Z=1 and Z=2 are separate worlds.

The model controls depth by controlling inter-layer impedance.
Deep computation = many low-Z coupled layers.
Shallow computation = few layers, high isolation.

This IS attention. Strong coupling between relevant layers,
weak coupling between irrelevant ones. The impedance map
IS the attention pattern.


DATA REPRESENTATION
===================

Everything is 0 or 1 at a position. How do you represent
larger values?

    Convention: multi-bit values occupy consecutive X positions
    at the same (y, z).

    8-bit value at channel 0:
        bit 0 = (0, y, z)
        bit 1 = (1, y, z)
        ...
        bit 7 = (7, y, z)

    X = bit index within the word.
    LSB at lowest X. MSB at highest X.

    32-bit integer: X positions 0-31.
    IEEE 754 float:  X positions 0-31 (sign, exponent, mantissa).
    ASCII character: X positions 0-7.
    String of N chars: N consecutive Y slots, each 8 X positions wide.

    Image: X = pixel column, Y = pixel row, Z = channel (R/G/B),
           8 bits per channel packed in sub-positions.

This is not a type system. There are no types. There are only
positions with values. The INTERPRETATION is determined by
which topology reads them. An adder topology interprets 32
positions as an integer. A convolution topology interprets
a 2D region as an image. Same bits. Different topology.
Different meaning.

The encoding is the topology, not the data.


I/O PROTOCOL
============

The lattice has edges. The edges are the I/O boundary.

    Injection:  set value at boundary position.
                Energy enters the lattice.

    Extraction: read value at boundary position.
                Energy leaves the lattice (observation tax applies).

The model interfaces at designated boundary positions.
These are not special. They're lattice positions like any other.
They just happen to be at the edge where outside meets inside.

    Input port:  (x, 0, 0)     — y=0 edge, z=0 surface
    Output port: (x, y_max, 0) — far edge, z=0 surface

Signals propagate from input to output through the topology.
The model injects. The lattice computes. The model reads.

For FPGA: pin N maps to lattice position (N, 0, 0).
For sensor: ADC sample → transducer → binary → inject.
For display: read output positions → DAC → output.

No driver. No protocol stack. Position IS the interface.


MULTI-LATTICE
=============

One substrate = one lattice. What about more?

Two lattices communicate through boundary coupling.
Output positions on lattice A connect to input positions
on lattice B through a physical link (wire, fiber, radio).

    Lattice A output: (x, y_max, 0) → physical channel
    Physical channel → Lattice B input: (x, 0, 0)

The coupling impedance of the physical channel determines
bandwidth and signal integrity. Matched impedance = full
transfer. Mismatched = reflection at the boundary.

This is networking without a network stack.
The physics of the inter-lattice link IS the protocol.

    Local bus (FPGA pin to FPGA pin): ~0 impedance mismatch.
    PCB trace: impedance = trace geometry. 50Ω matched.
    Long cable: impedance matching at both ends.

Address space across lattices:

    (lattice_id, x, y, z) at their respective T

    lattice_id is implicit in the physical connection.
    Position (5, 0, 0) on lattice A is NOT the same as
    position (5, 0, 0) on lattice B.
    They're in different substrates. Different T.

Hierarchical: a lattice position can map to an entire
sub-lattice. Position (10, 10, 0) on the parent lattice
is the I/O boundary of a child lattice with its own internal
topology. This is recursive. Lattices of lattices.


ADDRESSING AT SCALE
===================

The binary format uses 10 bits for X, 10 for Y, 8 for Z.
That's 1024 × 1024 × 256 = ~268 million spatial positions.
T indexes the states. More T = more history, not more space.

For larger lattices, the coordinate space is hierarchical:

    Level 0: 1024 × 1024 × 256 (single lattice, 28 bits)
    Level 1: 1024 lattices of Level 0 (38 bits)
    Level 2: 1024 clusters of Level 1 (48 bits)

The hierarchy is not virtual. Each level is a physical
substrate boundary. Level 0 = one FPGA. Level 1 = one board.
Level 2 = one rack.

Within a level, coordinates are flat and fast.
Across levels, signals cross a physical boundary (observation
tax applies at each crossing).



