BINARY ENCODING
===============

The model speaks binary. Here is the wire format.

Every XYZT instruction is 64 bits:

    [OP:4] [X:10] [Y:10] [Z:8] [VALUE:16] [FLAGS:16]

    OP codes:
        0x0  NOP       — no operation
        0x1  SET       — set value at (x,y,z). VALUE = distinction.
        0x2  GET       — read value at (x,y,z). Returns to output.
        0x3  WIRE      — connect (x,y,z) to target.
                         FLAGS[0:1]  = junction type (XOR/AND/OR/MAJ)
                         FLAGS[2:11] = target X
        0x4  IMPEDANCE — set Z-param at (x,y,z). VALUE = impedance.
        0x5  INJECT    — inject signal at (x,y,z). VALUE = amplitude.
        0x6  PROBE     — read with impedance. FLAGS[8:15] = probe Z.
        0x7  WALL      — set impedance rectangle. X,Y = start.
                         VALUE[0:7] = end X, VALUE[8:15] = end Y.
                         FLAGS[0:7] = impedance value.
        0x8  OPEN      — lower impedance at (x,y,z) to VALUE.
        0x9  CLOSE     — raise impedance at (x,y,z) to max.
        0xA  TICK      — advance one propagation step.
        0xB  RUN       — advance N steps. VALUE = N.
        0xC  LEARN     — Hebbian learning pass. VALUE = rate.
        0xD  PRUNE     — remove edges below VALUE threshold.
        0xE  SPAWN     — create edges where correlation > VALUE.
        0xF  HALT      — stop. T-break.

    FLAGS (per-instruction modifiers):
        bit 0-1:  junction type for WIRE
                  (00=XOR, 01=AND, 10=OR, 11=MAJ)
        bit 2-11: secondary coordinate (target X for WIRE,
                  target Y for multi-coord ops)
        bit 12:   immediate mode (VALUE is literal)
        bit 13:   boundary flag (position is at lattice edge)
        bit 14:   learning enable (edge adapts after creation)
        bit 15:   gain flag (position is a restoration point)

A stream of 64-bit words IS the program.
No header. No metadata. No ELF format.
First word executes immediately. Last word is HALT or loops.


COLD BOOT
=========

On power-up, the lattice is empty. No impedance. No topology.
No signals. Nothing. Something external must inject the first
configuration. That something is the bootstrap ROM.

The bootstrap ROM is a minimal hardwired topology baked into
the substrate — the only part of XYZT that is not runtime
configurable. It exists before the first instruction.

On FPGA: the bitstream IS the bootstrap ROM.
On PCB: the trace geometry IS the bootstrap ROM.
On simulation: the initial array values ARE the bootstrap ROM.

The bootstrap ROM contains:

    1. Lattice dimensions (hardwired at synthesis/fabrication)
    2. I/O port positions (which edge positions are external)
    3. A single gain region at the I/O boundary (so the first
       injected signal doesn't immediately die)
    4. The noise floor threshold (substrate-dependent constant)

Everything else is injected at runtime by the model.

Boot sequence:

    Power on → bootstrap ROM active → I/O ports alive →
    model injects impedance topology → model injects wiring →
    model injects data → lattice propagates → model reads

The model IS init. The first topology it writes IS pid 1.


INIT: THE FIRST PROCESS
========================

On Unix, init is pid 1 — the ancestor of all processes.
On XYZT, init is the first impedance topology the model writes.

What does init do? It creates the first boundary.

    Step 1: WALL the lattice into regions.
            One region for the model's workspace.
            One region for the first computation.
            Impedance wall between them.

    Step 2: WIRE the model's workspace.
            Input ports → probe positions.
            This is the model's sensory loop.
            It can observe the lattice and react.

    Step 3: OPEN a port between regions.
            The model can now inject into the computation region.

    Step 4: Write the first real program into the computation region.

Init creates isolation first, connection second.
The model gives itself a workspace before doing anything else.
This is the XYZT kernel: the topology that manages topologies.


BOOTSTRAP SEQUENCE (FULL)
=========================

    0. Power on. Bootstrap ROM active. I/O alive.

    1. Model injects init topology:
        WALL(0, 0, 0, dim/2, dim)    — split lattice in half
        IMPEDANCE on workspace side   — model's observation region
        WIRE probes in workspace      — sensory loop

    2. Model opens port to computation region:
        OPEN(dim/2, y, 0)            — controlled channel

    3. Model writes program into computation region:
        IMPEDANCE for crystals, cavities, mirrors
        WIRE for junctions
        IMPEDANCE for gain regions (signal restoration)

    4. Model injects data:
        SET at input positions

    5. Model starts computation:
        RUN(N)                        — propagate N steps

    6. Model reads results:
        PROBE at output positions     — high-Z non-destructive

    7. Model decides what to do next:
        More data? → repeat from step 4.
        New program? → repeat from step 3.
        Expand? → WALL new region, repeat from step 2.

There is no step 8. That IS the OS.


EXAMPLE: 2-BIT ADDER
=====================

Inputs:
    (0,0,0) = A0    (bit 0 of A)
    (1,0,0) = A1    (bit 1 of A)
    (2,0,0) = B0    (bit 0 of B)
    (3,0,0) = B1    (bit 1 of B)

Topology:
    XOR_0: (0,0,0) ⊕ (2,0,0) → (0,0,1)     // A0 XOR B0 = S0
    AND_0: (0,0,0) ∧ (2,0,0) → (1,0,1)     // A0 AND B0 = C0

    XOR_1: (1,0,0) ⊕ (3,0,0) → (2,0,1)     // A1 XOR B1
    AND_1: (1,0,0) ∧ (3,0,0) → (3,0,1)     // A1 AND B1

    XOR_2: (2,0,1) ⊕ (1,0,1) → (0,0,2)     // (A1 XOR B1) XOR C0 = S1
    AND_2: (2,0,1) ∧ (1,0,1) → (1,0,2)     // (A1 XOR B1) AND C0

    OR:    (3,0,1) ∨ (1,0,2) → (2,0,2)     // C1 OR carry = S2

Outputs:
    (0,0,1) = S0    (bit 0 of sum)
    (0,0,2) = S1    (bit 1 of sum)
    (2,0,2) = S2    (bit 2 of sum / carry out)

A=3 (11), B=1 (01). Expected: 3+1=4 (100). S0=0, S1=0, S2=1.

Set the inputs. Topology exists. Outputs appear.
No clock. No instruction fetch. Just propagation.



